[
    {
        "        Richard Bedford Bennett, 1st Viscount Bennett,  was a Canadian lawyer, businessman and politician. He served as the 11th ": null
    },
    {
        "prime minister of Canada": "Prime Minister Of Canada"
    },
    {
        ", in office from 1930 to 1935. He led the ": null
    },
    {
        "Conservative Party": "Conservative Party Of Canada"
    },
    {
        " from 1927 to 1938.     Bennetts prime ministership is widely regarded as a failure by historians, although he left lasting legacies in the form of the ": null
    },
    {
        "Canadian Broadcasting Corporation": "Canadian Broadcasting Corporation"
    },
    {
        " and the ": null
    },
    {
        "Bank of Canada": "Bank Of Canada"
    },
    {
        " .     Bennett was born in ": null
    },
    {
        "Hopewell Hill, New Brunswick": "Hopewell Hill, New Brunswick"
    },
    {
        ", and grew up in nearby ": null
    },
    {
        "Hopewell Cape": "Hopewell Cape"
    },
    {
        ". He studied law at ": null
    },
    {
        "Dalhousie University": "Dalhousie University"
    },
    {
        ", graduating in 1893, and in 1897 moved to ": null
    },
    {
        "Calgary": "Calgary"
    },
    {
        " to establish a law firm in partnership with ": null
    },
    {
        "James Lougheed": "James Alexander Lougheed"
    },
    {
        ".     Bennett served in the ": null
    },
    {
        "Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories": "Legislative Assembly Of The Northwest Territories"
    },
    {
        " from 1898 to 1905, and later in the ": null
    },
    {
        "Alberta Legislature": "Alberta Legislature"
    },
    {
        " from 1909 to 1911. He was the inaugural leader of the ": null
    },
    {
        "Alberta Conservative Party": "Alberta Conservative Party"
    },
    {
        " from 1905, resigning upon his election to the ": null
    },
    {
        "House of Commons": "House Of Commons Of Canada"
    },
    {
        " in 1911. From 1920 to 1921, Bennett was ": null
    },
    {
        "Minister of Justice": "Minister Of Justice"
    },
    {
        " under ": null
    },
    {
        "Arthur Meighen": "Arthur Meighen"
    },
    {
        ". He also served briefly as ": null
    },
    {
        "Minister of Finance": "Minister Of Finance"
    },
    {
        " in Meighens second government in 1926, which lasted just a month. Meighen resigned the Conservative Partys leadership after its defeat at the ": null
    },
    {
        "1926 election": "1926 Canadian Federal Election"
    },
    {
        ", with Bennett elected as his replacement .     Bennett became prime minister after the ": null
    },
    {
        "1930 election": "1930 Canadian Federal Election"
    },
    {
        ", where the Conservatives won a landslide victory over ": null
    },
    {
        "Mackenzie Kings": "William Lyon Mackenzie King"
    },
    {
        " Liberal Party": "Liberal Party Of Canada"
    },
    {
        ". He was the first prime minister to represent a constituency in Alberta. The main difficulty during Bennetts prime ministership was the ": null
    },
    {
        "Great Depression": "Great Depression In Canada"
    },
    {
        ". He and his party initially tried to combat the crisis with  laissez-faire  policies, but these were largely ineffective. However, over time Bennetts government became increasingly interventionist, attempting to replicate the popular ": null
    },
    {
        "New Deal": "New Deal"
    },
    {
        " enacted by ": null
    },
    {
        "Franklin Roosevelt": "Franklin Roosevelt"
    },
    {
        " to the south. This about-face prompted a split within Conservative ranks, and was regarded by the general public as evidence of incompetence.     Bennett suffered a landslide defeat at the ": null
    },
    {
        "1935 election": "1935 Canadian Federal Election"
    },
    {
        ", with Mackenzie King returning for a third term. Bennett remained leader of the Conservative Party until 1938, when he retired to England.     He was created Viscount Bennett, the only Canadian prime minister to be honoured with elevation to the ": null
    },
    {
        "peerage": "Peerage Of The United Kingdom"
    },
    {
        ".       Bennett was born on 3 July 1870, when his mother, Henrietta Stiles, was visiting at her parents home in ": null
    },
    {
        "Hopewell Hill, New Brunswick": "Hopewell Hill, New Brunswick"
    },
    {
        ", Canada. He was the eldest of six children, and grew up nearby at the ": null
    },
    {
        "Bay of Fundy": "Bay Of Fundy"
    },
    {
        " home of his father, Henry John Bennett, in ": null
    },
    {
        "Hopewell Cape": "Hopewell Cape"
    },
    {
        ", the ": null
    },
    {
        "shire town": "Shire Town"
    },
    {
        " of ": null
    },
    {
        "Albert County": "Albert County"
    },
    {
        ", then a town of 1,800 people.     His father descended from English ancestors who had emigrated to ": null
    },
    {
        "Connecticut": "Connecticut"
    },
    {
        " in the 17th century.  His great-great-grandfather, Zadock Bennett, migrated from ": null
    },
    {
        "New London, Connecticut": "New London, Connecticut"
    },
    {
        ", to ": null
    },
    {
        "Nova Scotia": "Nova Scotia"
    },
    {
        " c. 1760, before the ": null
    },
    {
        "American Revolution": "American Revolution"
    },
    {
        ", as one of the ": null
    },
    {
        "New England Planters": "New England Planters"
    },
    {
        " who took the lands forcibly removed from the deported ": null
    },
    {
        "Acadians": "Acadian"
    },
    {
        "during the ": null
    },
    {
        "Great Upheaval": "Great Upheaval"
    },
    {
        ".     R. B. Bennetts family was poor, subsisting mainly on the produce of a small farm. His early days inculcated a lifelong habit of thrift. The driving force in his family was his mother. She was a Wesleyan ": null
    },
    {
        "Methodist": "Methodist"
    },
    {
        " and passed this faith and the ": null
    },
    {
        "Protestant ethic": "Protestant Ethic"
    },
    {
        " on to her son. Bennetts father does not appear to have been a good provider for his family, though the reason is unclear. He operated a general store for a while and tried to develop some ": null
    },
    {
        "gypsum": "Gypsum"
    },
    {
        " deposits.     The Bennetts had previously been a relatively prosperous family, operating a shipyard in Hopewell Cape, but the change to steam-powered vessels in the mid-19th century meant the gradual winding down of their business. However, the household was a literate one, subscribing to three newspapers. They were strong ": null
    },
    {
        "Conservatives": "Conservatism"
    },
    {
        "; indeed one of the largest and last ships launched by the Bennett shipyard was the Sir John A. Macdonald .     Educated in the local school, Bennett was a very good student, but something of a loner. In addition to his ": null
    },
    {
        "Protestant": "Protestant"
    },
    {
        " faith, Bennett grew up with an abiding love of the ": null
    },
    {
        "British Empire": "British Empire"
    },
    {
        ", then at its apogee. A small legacy his mother received opened the doors for him to attend the ": null
    },
    {
        "Normal school": "Normal School"
    },
    {
        " in ": null
    },
    {
        "Fredericton": "Fredericton"
    },
    {
        ", where he trained to be a teacher; he then taught for several years at Irishtown, north of ": null
    },
    {
        "Moncton": "Moncton"
    },
    {
        ", saving his money for law school. Canadas Prime Ministers: Macdonald to Trudeau , edited by Ramsay Cook and Real Belanger, University of Toronto Press, 2007, p. 300,        One day, while Bennett was crossing the ": null
    },
    {
        "Miramichi River": "Miramichi River"
    },
    {
        " on the ferry boat, a well-dressed lad about nine years younger came over to him and struck up a conversation. This was the beginning of an improbable but important friendship with ": null
    },
    {
        "Max Aitken": "Max Aitken"
    },
    {
