    {
        " 1964, Longmans Canada            As the leader of the Conservative party, Bennett adapted its program, organization image to promote more rapid modernization of Canada. The New Deal was largely a mirror of the American program. The party was torn between reaction and reform, with deep internal factionalism that led to its defeat in 1935. Bennetts critics on the left had the last word, and textbooks typically portray him as a hard-driving capitalist, pushing for American-style high tariffs and British-style imperialism, while ignoring his reform efforts. Larry A. Glassford, Reaction and Reform: The Politics of the Conservative Party under R.B. Bennett, 1927-1938            By defeating the ": null
    },
    {
        "William Lyon Mackenzie King": "William Lyon Mackenzie King"
    },
    {
        " in the ": null
    },
    {
        "1930 federal election": "1930 Canadian Federal Election"
    },
    {
        ", he had the misfortune of taking office during the ": null
    },
    {
        "Great Depression": "Great Depression"
    },
    {
        ". Bennett tried to combat the depression by increasing trade within the ": null
    },
    {
        "British Empire": "British Empire"
    },
    {
        " and imposing ": null
    },
    {
        "tariffs": "Tariffs"
    },
    {
        " for imports from outside the Empire, promising that his measures would blast Canadian exports into world markets. His success was limited however, and his own wealth and impersonal style alienated many struggling Canadians.     While he was the first Prime Minister representing a constituency in Alberta, his party only won four of the provinces 16 seats. His speeches to the Empire Clubs in ": null
    },
    {
        "Toronto": "Toronto"
    },
    {
        " and ": null
    },
    {
        "Montreal": "Montreal"
    },
    {
        ", when chairman of the House of Commons Committee on Representation under Borden, that while settlers from the United States were suitable to be included with those entitled to vote, they however lacked the noble element normally found in the British, caused controversy. At the time, the federal government was required, under a Statute of British Parliament, to re-adjust representation to Alberta and Saskatchewan based on the 1911 census. The re-adjustment made to the four western provinces at the time can only be correlated if only those having British and French origins are considered.     When his ": null
    },
    {
        "Imperial Preference": "Imperial Preference"
    },
    {
        " policy failed to generate the desired result, Bennetts government had no real contingency plan. The partys pro-business and pro-banking inclinations provided little relief to the millions of increasingly desperate and agitated unemployed. Despite the economic crisis, ": null
    },
    {
        "laissez-faire": "Laissez-Faire"
    },
    {
        " persisted as the guiding economic principle of Conservative Party ideology; similar attitudes dominated worldwide as well during this era. Government relief to the unemployed was considered a disincentive to individual initiative, and was therefore only granted in the most minimal amounts and attached to work programs. An additional concern of the federal government was that large numbers of disaffected unemployed men concentrating in urban centres created a volatile situation. As an alternative to bloodshed on the streets , the stop-gap solution for unemployment chosen by the Bennett government was to establish military-run and -styled relief camps in remote areas throughout the country, where single unemployed men toiled for twenty cents a day.  Any relief beyond this was left to provincial and municipal governments, many of which were either insolvent or on the brink of bankruptcy, and which railed against the inaction of other levels of government. Partisan differences began to sharpen on the question of government intervention in the economy, since lower levels of government were largely in Liberal hands, and protest movements were beginning to send their own parties into the political mainstream, notably the ": null
    },
    {
        "Cooperative Commonwealth Federation": "Cooperative Commonwealth Federation"
    },
    {
        " and ": null
    },
    {
        "William Aberharts": "William Aberhart"
    },
    {
        " Social Credit Party": "Social Credit Party Of Alberta"
    },
    {
        " in ": null
    },
    {
        "Alberta": "Alberta"
    },
    {
        ".     In July 1931, Bennetts government passed the ": null
    },
    {
        "Unemployment and Farm Relief Act": "Unemployment And Farm Relief Act"
    },
    {
        " in an effort to stanch the depression, but events were rapidly falling out of their control.          Bennett hosted the 1932 ": null
    },
    {
        "Imperial Economic Conference": "British Empire Economic Conference"
    },
    {
        " in ": null
    },
    {
        "Ottawa": "Ottawa"
    },
    {
        "; this was the first time Canada had hosted the meetings. It was attended by the leaders of the independent dominions of the British Empire . Bennett dominated the meetings, which were ultimately unproductive, due to the inability of leaders to agree on policies, mainly to combat the economic woes dominating the world at the time. Mr. Prime Minister 1867-1964, by ": null
    },
    {
        "Bruce Hutchison": "Bruce Hutchison"
    },
    {
        ", Toronto 1964, Longmans Canada.       A nickname that would stick with Bennett for the remainder of his political career, Iron Heel Bennett , came from a 1932 speech he gave in Toronto that ironically, if unintentionally, alluded to ": null
    },
    {
        "Jack Londons": "Jack London"
    },
    {
        "socialist ": null
    },
    {
        "novel": "The Iron Heel"
    },
    {
        ":     What do they offer you in exchange for the present order? Socialism, Communism, dictatorship. They are sowing the seeds of unrest everywhere. Right in this city such propaganda is being carried on and in the little out of the way places as well. And we know that throughout Canada this propaganda is being put forward by organizations from foreign lands that seek to destroy our institutions. And we ask that every man and woman put the iron heel of ruthlessness against a thing of that kind. The quote is from: ; the irony of the allusion is noted in      Reacting to fears of ": null
    },
    {
        "communist": "Communist"
    },
    {
        " subversion, Bennett invoked the controversial ": null
    },
    {
        "Section 98": "Section 98"
    },
    {
        " of the ": null
    },
    {
        "Criminal Code": "Criminal Code"
    },
    {
        ". Enacted in the aftermath of the ": null
    },
    {
        "Winnipeg general strike": "Winnipeg General Strike"
    },
    {
        ", section 98 dispensed with the ": null
    },
    {
        "presumption of innocence": "Presumption Of Innocence"
    },
    {
        " in outlawing potential threats to the state: specifically, anyone belonging to an organization that officially advocated the violent overthrow of the government. Even if the accused had never committed an act of violence or personally supported such an action, they could be incarcerated merely for attending meetings of such an organization, publicly speaking in its defense, or distributing its literature.  Despite the broad power authorized under section 98, it targeted specifically the ": null
    },
    {
        "Communist Party of Canada": "Communist Party Of Canada"
    },
    {
        ". Eight of the top party leaders, including ": null
    },
    {
        "Tim Buck": "Tim Buck"
    },
    {
        ", were arrested on 11 August 1931 and convicted under section 98. This plan to stamp out communism backfired, however, and proved to be a damaging embarrassment for the government, especially after Buck was the target of an apparent ": null
    },
    {
        "assassination": "Assassination"
    },
    {
        " attempt. While confined to his cell during a ": null
    },
    {
        "prison riot": "Prison Riot"
    },
    {
        ", despite not participating in the riot, shots were fired into his cell. When an ": null
    },
    {
        "agit-prop": "Agit-Prop"
    },
    {
        " play": "Play"
    },
    {
        " depicting these events,  Eight Men Speak , was suppressed on 4 December 1933 by the Toronto police, a protest meeting was held where Communist politician ": null
    },
    {
        "A. E. Smith": "Albert Edward Smith"
    },
    {
        " repeated the plays allegations, and he was consequently arrested for ": null
    },
    {
        "sedition": "Sedition"
    },
    {
        ". This created a storm of public protest, compounded when Buck was called as a witness to the trial and repeated the allegations in open court. Although the remarks were stricken from the record, they still discredited the prosecutions case and Smith was acquitted. As a result, the governments case against Buck lost any credibility, and Buck and his comrades were released early and fêted as heroic champions of ": null
    },
    {
        "civil liberties": "Civil Liberties"
    },
    {
        ".          Having survived section 98, and benefiting from the public sympathy wrought by persecution, Communist Party members set out to organize workers in the relief camps set up by the ": null
    },
    {
        "Unemployment and Farm Relief Act": "Unemployment And Farm Relief Act"
    },
    {
        ". Camp workers laboured on a variety of infrastructure projects, including such things as municipal airports, roads, and park facilities, along with a number of other make-work schemes. Conditions in the camps were poor, not only because of the low pay, but also the lack of recreational facilities, isolation from family and friends, poor quality food, and the use of ": null
    },
    {
        "military discipline": "Military Discipline"
    },
    {
        ". Communists thus had ample grounds on which to organize camp workers, although the workers were there of their own volition.  The ": null
    },
    {
        "Relief Camp Workers Union": "Relief Camp Workers Union"
    },
    {
        " was formed and affiliated with the ": null
